text.section:
The board may refuse to issue a license or permit, or may suspend, revoke, impose probationary conditions upon, impose an administrative fine, issue a written reprimand or admonishment, or any combination thereof regarding any licensee or permit holder upon proof that the licensee or permit holder has:
Committed any act of dishonesty or corruption. If the act constitutes a crime, conviction in a criminal proceeding is not a condition precedent to disciplinary action. Upon conviction of the crime, the judgment and sentence are presumptive evidence at the ensuing disciplinary hearing of the guilt of the licensee or applicant. Conviction includes all instances in which a plea of no contest is the basis of the conviction;
Misrepresented or concealed a material fact in obtaining a license, or in reinstatement thereof;
Committed any unfair, false, misleading, or deceptive act or practice;
Been incompetent or negligent in the practice of marriage and family therapy;
Violated any state statute or administrative regulation governing the practice of marriage and family therapy or any activities undertaken by a marriage and family therapist;
Failed to comply with an order issued by the board or an assurance of voluntary compliance;
Violated the code of ethics as set forth by the board in administrative regulations; or
Violated any applicable provision of any federal or state law.
